Introduction

The NBA is one of the biggest sports leagues in the United States, with the average team being worth $2.12 billion as of 2020 [https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbespr/2020/02/11/the-business-of-basketball-forbes-releases-22nd-annual-nba-team-valuations/#352c7b7f75ff]. Like many other major league sports, data science and analytics have become an increasingly prevalent tool for teams to try and gain a competitive advantage, and has impacted the way the game is thought about and played, as seen for example by its role in increasing the importance of the 3-point shot [https://towardsdatascience.com/nba-data-analytics-changing-the-game-a9ad59d1f116]. To allow teams to select young new players in a fair manner, an annual draft is held, which has consisted of two rounds (with every team given a pick in the first and second round) since 1989. Any players not selected in those two rounds are allowed to try out and sign with any interested team. More information about the evolution and the current format of the draft can be read here [http://www.nba.com/history/draft_evolution.html]. This project is aimed to be an interesting tutorial that introduces the reader to the basic aspects of data science by showing how it can be applied to understanding the value and importance of draft picks within the annual NBA draft. Hopefully, the analysis within here can help the reader gain a sense for the overall value players taken at different points in the draft typically add to their team. Understanding this value is vital for teams to evaluate the value of their picks, and consider potential trades of draft picks with other teams to try and get the best value and chance at creating the best team possible.

The dataset we are using can be found at https://www.kaggle.com/justinas/nba-players-data. The data is comprised of individual specific seasons for each NBA player from the 1996-97 to 2016-17 seasons. For this specific project, the important parts of this data that we will be making use of are the statistics it lists for each individual season for a given player, and the information regarding where they were selected in the NBA draft (if they were selected).

Data processing is one of the most important steps to analyse data. Load the data into dataframe with appropriate names that it can accurately describe the data. After loading the data, we now create a tidier data table with some characteristics changed in order to set it up for analysis later. We create a new column called undrafted that is true if that player was undrafted, and false if not. We then replace entries that had undrafted listed as their draft_year, draft_round, and draft_number with NA instead. We convert the draft_round, draft_year, and draft_number columns to be integers instead of characters. You should learn to get rid of missing data appropriately before doing any actual analysis to avoid any unnecessary errors. Additionally, since the NBA switched to a 2-round draft in 1989, to accurately measure the value of draft picks in the modern draft format, were going to filter out any players who were drafted before 1989. We also exclude erroneous entries that have draft_round listed as greater than 2.

tidy_nba <-
  nba_tab %>%
mutate(Undrafted = ifelse(draft_round == "Undrafted" | draft_year == "Undrafted" |
                        draft_number == "Undrafted",TRUE,FALSE)) %>%
  replace_with_na_all(condition = ~.x == "Undrafted")

tidy_nba$draft_round <- as.integer(tidy_nba$draft_round)
tidy_nba$draft_year <- as.integer(tidy_nba$draft_year)
tidy_nba$draft_number <- as.integer(tidy_nba$draft_number)

tidy_nba <-
  filter(tidy_nba, (draft_year >= 1989 | is.na(draft_year)) &
           (draft_round <= 2 | is.na(draft_round)))

head(tidy_nba)

This code creates a dataframe that only includes players in their rookie seasons. The first season this dataset has data from is the 1996-1997 season. Some players who played in the 1996 had been drafted before that year, and because undrafted players do not have a draft_year listed and so it cannot be determined whether 1996 was their first season or not, were only looking at all rookie seasons starting from 1997 instead.

# distinct() removes all duplicates based on the player_name variable if there's
# already another row with that value. The tidy_nba is sorted by season, so it'll
# remove all seasons besides their first season for all players.
rookie_after_1997_df <-
  tidy_nba %>%
  distinct(player_name, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  filter(season != "1996-97")

rookie_after_1997_df

(2)team_abbreviation:Abbreviated name of the team the player played for (at the end of the season) (3)age:Age of the player (4)player_height:Height of the player (in centimeters) (5)player_weight:Weight of the player (in kilograms) (6)college:Name of the college the player attended (7)countryName of the country the player was born in (not necessarily the nationality) (8)draft_year:The year the player was drafted (9)draft_round:The draft round the player was picked (10)draft_number:The number at which the player was picked in his draft round (11)gp:Games played throughout the season (12)pts:Average number of points scored (13)reb:Average number of rebounds grabbed (14)ast:Average number of assists distributed (15)net_rating:Teams point differential per 100 possessions while the player is on the court (16)oreb_pct:Percentage of available offensive rebounds the player grabbed while he was on the floor (17)dreb_pct:Percentage of available defensive rebounds the player grabbed while he was on the floor (18)usg_pct:Percentage of team plays used by the player while he was on the floor (FGA + Possession Ending FTA + TO) / POSS) (19)ts_pct:Measure of the players shooting efficiency that takes into account free throws, 2 and 3 point shots (PTS / (2(FGA + 0.44 FTA))) (20)ast_pct:Percentage of teammate field goals the player assisted while he was on the floor

Draft Pick Distribution

Now we will make a pie chart to show the percentage of players taken in what set of picks make up the NBA playerbase during the 2016-17 season. Trying to assign a percentage for each of the 60 picks in the draft would divide the data into a lot of small ranges without many data points, but simply dividing it up into the 1st round, 2nd round, and undrafted might not be as informative and precise as we would like, especially since previous data analysis has shown that there seems to be a big difference between players chosen at the beginning of the first round and towards the end of the second round specifically. When you run into this problem in data science where you want to group some entities together into groups depending on the value of some attribute, you can use what is called discretization (although draft_number is already a discrete variable here). This is usually used to transform continuous values into discrete values, and typically either places values into a specified number of intervals regardless of how many values fit into each one, or places an equal number of values into each interval, with the range of the intervals varying to match the distribution. [cite hectors lecture notes 22.2.1]. To learn more about when to use discretization and how different ways to implement it, you can read (the article here)[https://towardsdatascience.com/an-introduction-to-discretization-in-data-science-55ef8c9775a2]

In R, discretization can be implemented using the cut function, as seen below. We use it here to divide the draft_number attribute into 6 intervals, with each interval containing 10 draft picks, then label the intervals with the inclusive range of picks they represent. First we make a pie chart representing all the players who played during the season, then we make another pie chart where all the rookies are excluded. Doing this should allow us to gain a better understanding of what draft picks usually turn out good enough to stay in the league to better understand player retention. It uses geom_bar() and coord_polar() from the ggplot2 package to make the pie charts.

# the breaks argument in cut() breaks the draft_number values into 6 distinct
# ranges, with the first number being an exclusive lower bound and the next
# being the inclusive upper bound as well as the exclusive lower bound for the
# next range, and so on.
discrete_picks_df <-
  tidy_nba %>%
  mutate(pick_range = cut(draft_number, breaks = c(0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60),
                             labels = c("1-10", "11-20", "21-30", "31-40", "41-50", "51-60")))

# Make the pick_range column be characters instead, then assign any entry
# that was undrafted the value of "Undrafted" for better naming purposes
discrete_picks_df$pick_range <- as.character(discrete_picks_df$pick_range)
discrete_picks_df$pick_range[is.na(discrete_picks_df$pick_range)] <- "Undrafted"

# Creates data frame that takes all the entries of players from the 2016-17
# season and counts how many players fell into which discretized range of draft
# picks. It then calculates what percentage of all players fell into which group
# that season.
season_discr_pick_percent_df <-
  filter(discrete_picks_df, season == "2016-17") %>%
  group_by(pick_range) %>%
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(range_percentage = n/sum(n)) %>%
  arrange(desc(pick_range))

# Creates the pie chart based on the data frame created above. subtracting half
# of the percentage from the y value helps ggplot optimize the position of the
# label on the chart.
ggplot(season_discr_pick_percent_df) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = "", y = range_percentage, fill = pick_range), stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y", start = 0) +
  theme_void() +
  geom_text(aes(x = 1, y = cumsum(range_percentage) - (range_percentage/2),
                label = scales::percent(range_percentage)))

# Create a dataframe similar to season_discr_pick_percent_df, but without any
# rookies. anti_join() does this by removing any players from the filtered
# discrete_picks_df for the 2016-17 season who appear on the list of rookies
# with the same name and their rookie season matching 2016-17. The rest is the
# same as before.
season_discr_pick_percent_nonrookies <-
  filter(discrete_picks_df, season == "2016-17") %>%
  anti_join(rookie_after_1997_df, by = c("player_name", "season")) %>%
  group_by(pick_range) %>%
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(range_percentage = n/sum(n)) %>%
  arrange(desc(pick_range))

# Use the same process as the previous pie chart to make the new one without any
# rookies.
ggplot(season_discr_pick_percent_nonrookies) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = "", y = range_percentage, fill = pick_range), stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y", start = 0) +
  theme_void() +
  geom_text(aes(x = 1, y = cumsum(range_percentage) - (range_percentage/2),
                label = scales::percent(range_percentage)))

Based on the pie charts, Players picked within the top ten picks made up almost a quarter of all players in the league in 2016, with each subsequent interval of ten picks making up about 3-5% less of the league than the previous interval. Somewhat surprisingly, 19% of the league consisted of undrafted players. However, this makes more sense considering that the NBA has 30 teams, each with a maximum roster of 15 players, with additional players needing to join teams when players get injured [https://www.nba.com/news/faq]. This results in a minimum of 450 players making a roster in 2016, with only 60 rookies getting drafted, so a sizeable amount of undrafted rookies are needed to fill out rosters. By comparing the two pie charts, you can better see how many rookies do not pan out. As a percent of all the NBA players playing in at least their second season in 2016, the proportion of top ten picks went up by 3%. The proportion for every interval of picks in the first round increased, whereas every interval of players drafted in the 2nd or who went undrafted decreased or stayed the same, indicating a higher turnover rate of players within those intervals. The proportion of undrafted players went from 19% to 14.6%, indicating an especially high rate of undrafted players not making it to their second season. Its also interesting to note that over 60% of the players playing in at least their second NBA season were drafted in the first round.

Regression and Prediction

Can the players performance statistics predict if they were drafted or not? We see that generally, undrafted players do not perform as well as those that were drafted, but is there a statistical backing for it? Well perform a logistic regression on the performance values that were chosen previously to see if we are able to predict if the player was drafted. A logistic regression is useful for this question as were trying to predict a binary value: drafted or undrafted. We had created an Undrafted column in our data to easily use this value. R is able to do this for us with the glm() function, summary() and confint() will output the calculations.

Notes: Players with less than 10 games were filtered out to remove possible outlier values. Total shot percentage was multiplied by 10 to fit the range more in line with other variables.

rm_under10 <- tidy_nba %>%
  filter(gp >= 10)
rm_under10$ts_pct <- rm_under10$ts_pct * 10

logit <- glm(formula = Undrafted ~ net_rating + gp + pts + ts_pct, data = rm_under10, family = "binomial")
summary(logit)

From the results, we actually see that our chosen performance metrics are not very good at predicting whether or not a player is drafted. Net rating, games played, and points all contain negative coefficients which means as those stats go up, the chance for them being drafted decreases. Intuitively, this doesnt make much sense as you would think better stats means higher chance to be drafted. This is likely due to the large spread in data among those variables. Among drafted and undrafted, there are players that perform well and poorly. The main driver in our logistic function is total shot percentage. This variable matches out intuition, and turns out to be the greatest predictor in whether a player was drafted or not.
